@saulshanabrook The standard reason for avoiding anonymous functions (including anonymous function expressions) is for debugging. For example, for callbacks provided to `Promise` methods, stack traces will include the function/method name when the function is named, thus allowing easier mapping of the problematic function to its source implementation (e.g., rather than searching for a line number, one can use `grep`). While benefits may be limited for one-off functions, the benefits increase for functions/methods/design patterns reused across a codebase. 

While named function expression support has improved in recent ECMAScript editions, historically, using them was not "best" practice, due to debugging and browser quirks (e.g., IE).

Lastly, moving the function body to a named function more clearly separates the usage of the function from its implementation and avoids common bracket matching issues (although this is obviated by modern IDE features such as automatic bracket pairing and highlighting, etc). Far too often, developers rely on nested inline anonymous functions which is generally bad practice because often the enclosing scopes include unnecessary identifiers and, without compiler tricks, results in unnecessary stack allocation. Better practice is using named functions at the highest possible scope to both limit a function's scope to what is absolutely necessary (e.g., only those parent scope identifiers which are needed by the function; commonly, this is the top-most module scope) and ensure that JS engines can minimize function creation and GC.

