Thanks @simonlingoogle .

Yes, In `Stop()`, we do go from `kAdding` to `kToRefresh`.  I added it in first implementation of SRP client with the idea to be safe in the case where client is stopped after we sent an update to server and while waiting for a response from it (there is a a comment in the code which tries to explain it):

```
void Client::Stop(Requester aRequester)
{
    // Change the state of host info and services so that they are
    // added/removed again once the client is started back. In the
    // case of `kAdding`, we intentionally move to `kToRefresh`
    // instead of `kToAdd` since the server may receive our add
    // request and the item may be registered on the server. This
    // ensures that if we are later asked to remove the item, we do
    // notify server.
```

In the new code handling the switch to a new server, we know that we have tried multiple times and waited long enough and received no response from server, so in this case, we manually switch to `kToAdd` (so that we remember we have not yet registered the host info and allow switch to server to happen if things continue to fail.

It's not the best (most clear) approach but it works. I will try to add a comment around `mHostInfo.SetState(kToAdd)` statement to explain this in the code. If you have any suggestions  or ideas around this, please let me know.

