`Process()` will not add the entry to network data immediately. It will add it after some random delay (up to `kMaxDelayToAdd` which is 3.5 seconds). 

```c++
    case kToAdd:
        // Our entry is ready to be added. If there are too few existing
        // entries, we start adding our entry (start the timer with a
        // random delay before adding the entry).

        if (aNumEntries < aDesiredNumEntries)
        {
            mUpdateTime = TimerMilli::GetNow() + Random::NonCrypto::GetUint32InRange(1, kMaxDelayToAdd);
            SetState(kAdding);
            Get<Publisher>().GetTimer().FireAtIfEarlier(mUpdateTime);
            LogUpdateTime();
        }
        break;
```
 
The main goal for this is to make sure existing entries in Network Data are not removed abruptly (or disappear for a while) when there is a flag/preference change.  If it was previously added in Network Data , we re-add it to Network Data with new flags.

An example situation for this in `RoutingManager` is if we see a router advertising a previous RIO route prefix with a higher preference, we don't want the change to preference to cause existing "external route" entry in Network data to be removed (which can then mess up traffic flow through BR).

Should we show an example of this?

```python
import .greeter as Self

name: public(String[10])

@external
def __init__(_name: String[10]):
    self.name = _name

@view
@external
def greet() -> String[16]:
    return concat("Hello ", Self(msg.sender).name())
```

